    "citation": "Yamamoto 2015 25162219",
    "population": "N: 156 (Japanese) Age: ~7±4.2 (0.42-15) WT: ~27±14",
    "model_type": "PK",
    "objective": "“to identify the optimum target dose of PHT and to assess the clinical efficacy of genotyping the CYP2C9*3, CYP2C19*2, and CCYP2C19*3 alleles in Japanese pediatric patients with epilepsy”",
    "covariates": "Tested: SEX, WT, VPA, CBZ, PHB, ZNS, CLBZ, TPM, CLNZ, nitrazepam, sulthiame, GBP, LMT, LVT, CYP2C9, CYP2C19 Included: WT, CYP2C9, CCYP2C19, sulthiame",
    "observations": "Although the analysis resulted in a simplified PK model (essentially modelling the correlation between dose and clearance), which allowed to individualise treatment. a statistically insignificant improvement in terms of withdrawal from PHT treatment and time to treatment failure was found when compared to conventional dosing, possibly due to a lack of power (n=17 individualised treatment vs n=139 conventional)",
    "dose": "Steady-state oral doses in patients",
    "structure": "Simplified PK",
    "equations": "ETD = theta1-theta2*log(WT)-theta3 *CYP2C9_3-theta4*CYP2C19_2-theta5*CYP2C19_3-theta6*SULTHIAME ETD is estimated target dose in mg/kg/day CYP2C9_3 is having the CYP2C9*3 genotype (0=no, 1=yes) CYP2C19_2 is having the CYP2C19*2 genotype (0=no, 1=yes) CYP2C19_3 is having the CYP2C19*3 genotype (0=no, 1=yes) SULTHIAME is concomitantly receiving treatment with sulthiame (0=no, 1=yes)",
    "parameter_values": "theta1=17.63 theta2=6.94 theta3=2.68 theta4=0.68 theta5=1.06 theta6=1.07",
    "validation": "No/Yes (validation by individualised treatment, n=17)"
  },
